We start by extracting the relevant numbers from the three statements.

Step 1. Debt to Asset Ratio  
• In the balance sheet, the “Debt” is represented by the Total Current Liabilities.  
• Total Current Liabilities = 1,124,588.25  
• Total Assets = 15,288,131.32  
• Debt to Asset Ratio = Total Liabilities / Total Assets  
  = 1,124,588.25 / 15,288,131.32  
  ≈ 0.0735  
Rounded to two decimals, this is 0.07.

Step 2. Gross Profit Margin  
• From the income statement:  
  Gross Profit = 2,741,764.34  
  Total Revenue = 5,991,764.34  
• Gross Profit Margin = Gross Profit / Total Revenue  
  = 2,741,764.34 / 5,991,764.34  
  ≈ 0.4576  
As a percentage this is 45.76%.

Step 3. Operating Cash Flow Ratio  
• From the cash flow statement:  
  Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities = 215,423.24  
• And from the balance sheet, using Total Current Liabilities = 1,124,588.25  
• Operating Cash Flow Ratio = Operating Cash Flow / Total Current Liabilities  
  = 215,423.24 / 1,124,588.25  
  ≈ 0.1916  
Rounded to two decimals, this is 0.19.

Thus, the final solution is:

{
  "solution": {
    "Debt to Asset Ratio": "0.07",
    "Gross Profit Margin": "45.76%",
    "Operating Cash Flow Ratio": "0.19"
  }
}
